[ProMED-mail recently posted a report of the mumps outbreak on the OSU campus in the city of Columbus, Ohio, at which time there was a total of 13 confirmed cases of mumps -- 7 women and 6 men between 18 and 22 years of age (ProMED-mail post Mumps - USA: (OH) university students 20140308.2321285). Now there are 24 community cases in Columbus and 95 cases reported in Franklin, Fairfield, Licking, and Union counties that surround Columbus in central Ohio, and Hamilton County (the county seat of Cincinnati in southwest Ohio) for a total of 119 cases, plus apparently an additional 10 cases in Delaware County, another county that surrounds Columbus. Columbus, the county seat of Franklin County, is also the capital of and the largest city in the US state of Ohio. For a map of Ohio that shows the location of this state's counties, see http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6d/Ohio_Counties_Labeled_White.svg.

The Ohio State University (OSU) is a large public research university in Columbus, Ohio, with about 28 000 undergraduates and more than 35 on-campus residence halls, with additional separate housing for graduate and professional students, plus multiple extra-curricular organizations where social mixing can occur to facilitate spread of the disease (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohio_State_University).

The mumps vaccine was licensed in 1967 and is usually administered as part of a combination vaccine that provides protection against measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/PDF/rr/rr4708.pdf). Live mumps virus vaccines in the US are derived from the Jeryl Lynn mumps vaccine strain. Post-licensure studies in the United States demonstrated that 1 dose of mumps vaccine was 78-91 percent effective in preventing clinical mumps with parotitis; a study from the United Kingdom indicated a vaccine effectiveness of 88 percent for 2 doses of MMR vaccine compared with 64 percent for a single dose (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5522a4.htm). The MMR vaccine in the United States is given in 2 doses: The 1st dose is given at 12-15 months of age and the 2nd dose before entering school, at 4-6 years of age (http://www.vaccines.gov/diseases/mumps/index.html).

Nevertheless, mumps outbreaks among vaccinated populations have been reported frequently during recent years, especially among college students where the intensity of exposure among students was presumed to have overcome the vaccine-induced immunity (http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/20/4/13-1681_article.htm).

The American College Health Association has recommended that colleges and universities require that students have documented receipt of 2 doses of MMR vaccine or have other acceptable evidence of measles, rubella, and mumps immunity before college enrollment (http://www.acha.org/topics/docs/CDC_ACHA_Mumps_Recommendations_Jul13.pdf). Immune globulin is not effective postexposure prophylaxis (http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/pubs/pinkbook/downloads/mumps.pdf). In an outbreak setting, MMR vaccine might reduce transmission to susceptible persons not yet exposed to the mumps virus. The CDC has evaluated use of a 3rd dose of MMR vaccine for mumps outbreak control during 2 previous mumps outbreaks in which transmission was sustained, despite high 2-dose coverage (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6148a2.htm). During both outbreaks, targeted vaccination was followed by a decrease in mumps incidence among the target group. - Mod.ML

